---

==================================================
3. OOP CONCEPTS USED
====================

1. Encapsulation

---

The Matrix class encapsulates:

* Data (2D vector)
* Methods (input, display, get, set)

Example:
class Matrix {
private:
int rows, cols;
vector<vector<double>> data;
};

This hides internal representation and exposes only controlled access.

---

2. Abstraction

---

User interacts with:

* loadMatrix()
* outputResult()
* compute() functions

They don’t need to know:

* how multiplication works internally
* how LU decomposition is computed

---

3. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

---

Each class has ONE job:

* Matrix → stores data
* Add → performs addition
* Multiply → performs multiplication
* GaussElimination → solves system
* LU → decomposition and solving

This makes system:

* Easy to debug
* Easy to extend

---

4. Modularity

---

Code is split into:

* operations/
* solvers/

This allows:

* independent development
* easy upgrades

---

5. Static Polymorphism (Compile-time behavior)

---

Operations use static functions:

Add::compute(A, B)

No object needed → clean and efficient

---

6. Reusability

---

Matrix class is reused across:

* operations
* solvers

Same structure used everywhere

---

==================================================
4. DATA FLOW (HOW SYSTEM WORKS)
===============================

Step-by-step flow:

1. User selects operation from menu
2. User loads matrix (manual/file)
3. Program stores matrix in Matrix class
4. Operation class processes data
5. Result is returned
6. Output is displayed or saved

---

==================================================
5. FLOWCHART (TEXTUAL)
======================

START
|
v
DISPLAY MENU
|
v
USER INPUT (CHOICE)
